<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA51">
<l>eḷiti liraṇṭaṭiyuṅ kāṇpataṟ keṉṉuḷḷan</l>
<l>teḷiyat teḷintoḻiyuñ cevvē – kaḷiyiṟ</l>
<l>poruntā tavaṉaip poraluṟ ṟariyā</l>
<l>yiruntāṉ ṟirunāma meṇ</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>In order to easily see [his] two [feet] – when my mind becomes clear</l>
<l>[they] remain fully clear<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The construction of this verse is ambiguous. I suggest to read a pūṭṭu vil: “in order to see the feet easily, count (or reflect upon) the holy names”. In this case eṉ uḷḷam | teḷiya+ teḷint’-oḻiyum cevvē has to be regarded as an inserted clause with elliptical subject, with the implication that the holy names are a means to make the mind clear, with the consequence that also the contemplation on the holy feet remains focussed. Moreover the function of oḻital as an auxiliary is not clear; it might mean remaining in a state once reached.</note> – count the holy names</l>
<l>of him who was [here] as a lion, taking up the fight</l>
<l>against the one who was improper in [his] pride.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Or: “who did not join him out of pride”</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
